\subsection{Supporting finite-module helpers}
\label{sec:gf_finite_helpers}

The following two file-internal helpers in the \texttt{GenericFreeness} namespace package
the finite \(A\)-module leaf in the two forms (flatness and module-finiteness) that the
chain and the geometric globalization consume. Both are already proved axiom-clean.

\begin{lemma}
[Flat localization away, finite module]
  \label{lem:gf_flat_finite}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.GenericFreeness.exists_flat_localizationAway_of_finite}
  \uses{lem:gf_finite_module}
  Let \(A\) be a noetherian domain and \(M\) a finite \(A\)-module. Then there exists
  \(f \in A\), \(f \ne 0\), such that \texttt{LocalizedModule (Submonoid.powers f) M} is
  \emph{flat} over \texttt{Localization.Away f}.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
  \uses{lem:gf_finite_module}
  By \cref{lem:gf_finite_module} the localized module is free over
  \texttt{Localization.Away f}; free modules are flat (\texttt{Module.Flat.of\_free}).
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}
[Free localization away, module-finite variant]
  \label{lem:gf_free_moduleFinite}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.GenericFreeness.exists_free_localizationAway_of_moduleFinite}
  \uses{lem:gf_finite_module}
  The module-finiteness packaging of \cref{lem:gf_finite_module}: for \(A\) a noetherian
  domain and \(M\) a module that is finite as an \(A\)-module, there exists \(f \ne 0\)
  with \texttt{LocalizedModule (Submonoid.powers f) M} free over
  \texttt{Localization.Away f}.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
  \uses{lem:gf_finite_module}
  Identical to \cref{lem:gf_finite_module}, packaged against the
  \texttt{Module.Finite} hypothesis.
\end{proof}


\begin{theorem}

